description.en:
This ontology covers the assets and condition assesment of a sewage system, mirroring the elements as defined per the national advisory leaflet DWA-M 150 of German sewage systems.

https://shop.dwa.de/DWA-M-150-Datenaustauschformat-fuer-die-Zustandserfassung-von-Entwaesserungssystemen-April-2010-Stand-korrigierte-Fassung-November-2018/M-150-10

This ontology was created as part of a Bachelors Thesis into an investigation of existing ontologies for underground infrastructure.

abstract.value:
Underground sewage infrastructure maintenance faces challenges due to fragmented, analog as�set data, hindering effective real-time monitoring and predictive maintenance. While digital twins offer promising technological potential, their practical implementation is constrained by complexdata integration challenges. Ontologies emerge as a critical approach to establish data relation�ships, providing a structured framework for bridging these systemic information gaps.

To address these gaps, this thesis introduces M150-Onto, a novel ontology designed to enhance the data management of sewage infrastructure by aligning with German regulatory frameworks and supporting interoperability among diverse data sources. This work explores an ontological approach with a particular focus on enabling more efficient querying and reasoning capabilities, allowing for advanced data retrieval and automated inference to support sewer infrastructure data
management. M150-Onto is developed and tested within Protégé, demonstrating its potential to improve data accessibility, integration, and predictive maintenance strategies. By identifying the strengths and limitations of current ontological frameworks and proposing M150- Onto as a targeted solution, this research contributes to the digital transformation of sewage in�frastructure management. The emphasis on efficient querying and reasoning enhances data�driven decision-making and sustainable maintenance strategies, addressing the critical need for improved infrastructure management amidst growing urbanization and environmental pressures.

editorialNote.value:
BIBO assert that a dcterms:Agent is an equivalent class to foaf:Agent.
This means that all the individuals belonging to the foaf:Agent class
also belongs to the dcterms:Agent class. This way, dcterms:contributor
can be used on foaf:Person, foaf:Organization, foaf:Agent and foaf:Group.
Even if this link is not done in neither the FOAF nor the DCTERMS ontologies this is a wide spread fact that is asserted by BIBO.

comment.en: A resource that acts or has the power to act.

The taxonomy of references includes the reference tables found in the advisory leaflet DWA-M 150.

DWA-M 150 categorizes reference tables by type of data. Examples are:
- Reference Table 105: Material Types (Class/Subclass: Reference/Material)
- Reference Table 202: Condition Assessment Coding Systems (Reference/CodingSystem)

Each subclass refers to a specific reference table in DWA-M 150, implied with the equivalentTo axiom "hasReferenceTable value "[RefTableNumber]"".

The different types found within a reference table are then listed as subclasses of the aforementioned subclass.
A passage selected from a larger work.
A spatial region or named place.

The taxonomy of components includes the main components of a sewage system according to the advisory leaflet DWA-M 150 and the reference table 128 "Object Types".

It is recommended to create individuals for Pipe Sections with the template:

` PipeSection[PipeSectionDesignation] `
` PipeSection[HG001] `

It is recommended to create individuals for Nodes with the template:

` Node[NodeDesignation] `
` Node[KG001] `

It is also recommended to declare that Components flows to another component with the asymmetric/irreflexive sub-object property `flowsTo` (Inverse: flowsFrom).

The ontology should then automatically reason, that all components flowing to / from each other are connected -- with its transitive super-object property "connectedWith".
A slide in a slideshow
A reference point against which other things can be evaluated or compared.
An excerpted collection of words.

An audio-visual document; film, video, and so forth.

The taxonomy of geometry includes the GIS geometry data of M150-Components. These include Geometry Object and Geometry Points.

It is recommended to create individuals for geometric objects with the template:

` GeoObject[PipeSection/Node Designation] `
` GeoObject[HG001]  ` for Pipe Section: Geometry Objects;
` GeoObject[KG001] ` for Node: Geometry Objects.

It is recommended to create individuals for geometric points with the template:

` GeoPoint[Geometry Point Description] `
` GeoPoint[GP001]  `.

`GeoObject`'s should be declared as the parent of 'GeoPoint''s with the object property `isParentOf`. (Inverse: isChildOf)

`GeoObject`'s should be declared as the renderer of a Component with the object property 'renders'. (Inverse: renderedBy)

Recommended practice is to express the date, date/time, or period of time according to ISO 8601-1 [[ISO 8601-1](https://www.iso.org/iso-8601-date-and-time-format.html)] or a published profile of the ISO standard, such as the W3C Note on Date and Time Formats [[W3CDTF](https://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime)] or the Extended Date/Time Format Specification [[EDTF](http://www.loc.gov/standards/datetime/)].
